Patient Selection for Diabetes Drug Testing¶

1. Project Instructions & Prerequisites¶

Project Instructions¶

Context: EHR data is becoming a key source of real-world evidence (RWE) for the pharmaceutical industry and regulators to make decisions on clinical trials. You are a data scientist for an exciting unicorn healthcare startup that has created a groundbreaking diabetes drug that is ready for clinical trial testing. It is a very unique and sensitive drug that requires administering the drug over at least 5-7 days of time in the hospital with frequent monitoring/testing and patient medication adherence training with a mobile application. You have been provided a patient dataset from a client partner and are tasked with building a predictive model that can identify which type of patients the company should focus their efforts testing this drug on. Target patients are people that are likely to be in the hospital for this duration of time and will not incur significant additional costs for administering this drug to the patient and monitoring.

In order to achieve your goal you must build a regression model that can predict the estimated hospitalization time for a patient and use this to select/filter patients for your study.

Expected Hospitalization Time Regression Model: Utilizing a synthetic dataset(denormalized at the line level augmentation) built off of the UCI Diabetes readmission dataset, students will build a regression model that predicts the expected days of hospitalization time and then convert this to a binary prediction of whether to include or exclude that patient from the clinical trial.

This project will demonstrate the importance of building the right data representation at the encounter level, with appropriate filtering and preprocessing/feature engineering of key medical code sets. This project will also require students to analyze and interpret their model for biases across key demographic groups.

Dataset¶

Due to healthcare PHI regulations (HIPAA, HITECH), there are limited number of publicly available datasets and some datasets require training and approval. So, for the purpose of this exercise, we are using a dataset from UC Irvine that has been modified for this course. Please note that it is limited in its representation of some key features such as diagnosis codes which are usually an unordered list in 835s/837s (the HL7 standard interchange formats used for claims and remits).

Data Schema: The dataset reference information can be found here. There are two CSVs that provide more details on the fields and some of the mapped values.

2. Learning Objectives¶

By the end of the project, you will be able to

  • Use the Tensorflow Dataset API to scalably extract, transform, and load datasets and build datasets aggregated at the line, encounter, and patient data levels(longitudinal)
  • Analyze EHR datasets to check for common issues (data leakage, statistical properties, missing values, high cardinality) by performing exploratory data analysis.
  • Create categorical features from Key Industry Code Sets (ICD, CPT, NDC) and reduce dimensionality for high cardinality features by using embeddings
  • Create derived features(bucketing, cross-features, embeddings) utilizing Tensorflow feature columns on both continuous and categorical input features
  • SWBAT use the Tensorflow Probability library to train a model that provides uncertainty range predictions that allow for risk adjustment/prioritization and triaging of predictions
  • Analyze and determine biases for a model for key demographic groups by evaluating performance metrics across groups by using the Aequitas framework

Determine Level of Dataset (Line or Encounter)¶

Based off of analysis of the data, what level is this dataset? Is it at the line or encounter level? Are there any key fields besides the encounter_id and patient_nbr fields that we should use to aggregate on? Knowing this information will help inform us what level of aggregation is necessary for future steps and is a step that is often overlooked.

With EHR datasets, there are three levels:

  • Line Level: A denormalized or disaggregated representation of all the things that might happen in a medical visit or encounter.
  • Encounter Level: Also known as the visit level, which is the aggregated information from the previously mentioned line level for one encounter. This information can be collapsed into a single row or arrays.
  • Longitudinal Level: Also known as the patient level view. This level aggregates the patient history and can show how the culmination of visits/encounter lead to some clinical impact.

Using the wrong EHR dataset level can lead to major errors with building models because data preparation is done with faulty assumptions and lead to serious error. For example, a common cause is the duplication of encounter information when you take a line-level dataset and treat it as an encounter level dataset.

If the total number of rows is greater than the number of unique encounters, it is at the line level.

In [11]:
try:
    assert len(df) > df['encounter_id'].nunique() 
    print("Line")
except:
    print("Not Line")

Line

If the total number of rows is equal to the number of unique encounters, it is at the encounter level.

In [12]:
try:
    assert len(df) == df['encounter_id'].nunique()
    print("Encounter")
except:
    print("Not Encounter")

Not Encounter

For the longitudinal or patient level, you will see multiple encounters grouped under a patient and you might not even see the encounter id field since this information is collapsed/aggregated under a unique patient id. In this case, the total number of rows should equal the total number of unique patients.

In [13]:
try:
    assert len(df) == df['patient_nbr'].nunique()
    print("Longitudinal")
except:
    print("Not Longitudinal")

Not Longitudinal

It seems that our data is at the line level, i.e. a denormalized or disaggregated representation of all the things that might happen in a medical visit or encounter.

To aggregate line level to encounter level, we could use the fields:

  • encounter_id
  • patient_nbr
  • principal_diagnosis_code

Questionable is, whether 0 is a placeholder for a missing value, or an actual number. Columns that have 0 as a value:

  • number_outpatient: Number of outpatient visits of the patient in the year preceding the encounter
  • number_inpatient: Number of inpatient visits of the patient in the year preceding the encounter
  • number_emergency: Number of emergency visits of the patient in the year preceding the encounter
  • num_procedures: Number of procedures (other than lab tests) performed during the encounter

If we look at the data dictionary descriptions above, any of these could take on actual zero value, so we well not treat 0 in these columns as missing values.

Note: Ideally, we want to clean the data properly. While this is the correct approach in the ordinary case, for this project we are using functions provided in utils.py, which assume certain things about the data, and if they don't receive what is expected, these functions can produce wrong results or errors. Thus, following advice from here, data is not cleaned in order to avoid an error with a built-in function later. To be able to count the missing value, we will instead create a copy of the df.

Which field(s) have high cardinality and why?¶

High-cardinality refers to columns with values that are very uncommon or unique. High-cardinality column values are typically identification numbers, email addresses, or user names. An example of a data table column with high-cardinality would be a USERS table with a column named USER_ID.

Select First Encounter for each Patient¶

In order to simplify the aggregation of data for the model, we will only select the first encounter for each patient in the dataset. This is to reduce the risk of data leakage of future patient encounters and to reduce complexity of the data transformation and modeling steps. We will assume that sorting in numerical order on the encounter_id provides the time horizon for determining which encounters come before and after another.

In [32]:
first_encounter_df = reduce_dim_df.sort_values(['encounter_id'], ascending=True).groupby('patient_nbr').head(1)
In [33]:
# unique patients in transformed dataset
unique_patients = first_encounter_df['patient_nbr'].nunique()
print("Number of unique patients:\t{}".format(unique_patients))

# unique encounters in transformed dataset
unique_encounters = first_encounter_df['encounter_id'].nunique()
print("Number of unique encounters:\t{}".format(unique_encounters))

original_unique_patient_number = reduce_dim_df['patient_nbr'].nunique()
# number of unique patients should be equal to the number of unique encounters and patients in the final dataset
assert original_unique_patient_number == unique_patients
assert original_unique_patient_number == unique_encounters

Aggregate Dataset to Right Level for Modeling¶

In order to provide a broad scope of the steps and to prevent students from getting stuck with data transformations, we have selected the aggregation columns and provided a function to build the dataset at the appropriate level. The 'aggregate_dataset" function can take the preceding dataframe with the 'generic_drug_name' field and transform the data appropriately for the project.

To make it simpler, we are creating dummy columns for each unique generic drug name and adding those are input features to the model. There are other options for data representation but this is out of scope for the time constraints of the course.

Next, looking at correlations, we want to pick variables that are highly correlated with the target (these make good features), but the variables themselves should be uncorrelated. If two features are correlated, the model really only needs one of them as the other does not bring additional ifnromation.

In [42]:
corr = df_msno.corr()

# Generate a mask for the upper triangle
mask = np.triu(np.ones_like(corr, dtype=bool))

f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(11, 9))
cmap = sns.diverging_palette(230, 20, as_cmap=True)
sns.heatmap(corr, mask=mask, cmap=cmap, vmax=.3, center=0,
            square=True, linewidths=.5, cbar_kws={"shrink": .5}, annot=True)

We see that out of all numeric variables, num_medications (0.46) and num_lab_procedures (0.32) are most correlated with our target variable. That's good, we want that.

We also see that number_diagnoses (0.22) and num_procedures (0.2) are correlated with the target variable. However, num_procedures is correlated with num_medications (0.41) and number_diagnoses with num_medications (0.25) and number_diagnoses (0.16). Therefore, we will not include these two features.

First of all, let's think from a context perspective. This dataset was not created for the purpose of this project, so naturally, not all features are actually available at or during the encounter. To predict time at hospital, the model cannot make use of features that are only determined at the end of the encounter, such as discharge_disposition_id (Integer identifier corresponding to 29 distinct values, for example, discharged to home, expired, and not available). We will therefore not include this variable.

ndc_code will not be used, as we use one-hot encoding of generic drugs instead.

This leaves us with:

  • admission_type_id - Integer identifier corresponding to 9 distinct values, for example, emergency, urgent, elective, newborn, and not available
  • admission_source_id - Integer identifier corresponding to 21 distinct values, for example, physician referral, emergency room, and transfer from a hospital
  • primary_diagnosis_code - Primary diagnosis code using ICD9 - CM code set
  • change Indicates if there was a change in diabetic medications (either dosage or generic name). Values: “change” and “no change”
  • readmitted - exclude, non-normal and non-uniform distribution

# from https://machinelearningmastery.com/feature-selection-with-categorical-data/
'''
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder
from sklearn.preprocessing import OrdinalEncoder
from sklearn.feature_selection import SelectKBest
from sklearn.feature_selection import mutual_info_classif
from matplotlib import pyplot

# prepare input data
def prepare_inputs(X_train, X_test):
    X_train_enc = pd.get_dummies(X_train)
    X_test_enc = pd.get_dummies(X_test)
    return X_train_enc, X_test_enc
 
# prepare target
def prepare_targets(y_train, y_test):
    le = LabelEncoder()
    le.fit(y_train)
    y_train_enc = le.transform(y_train)
    y_test_enc = le.transform(y_test)
    return y_train_enc, y_test_enc
 
# feature selection
def select_features(X_train, y_train, X_test):
    fs = SelectKBest(score_func=mutual_info_classif, k='all')
    fs.fit(X_train, y_train)
    X_train_fs = fs.transform(X_train)
    X_test_fs = fs.transform(X_test)
    return X_train_fs, X_test_fs, fs

X = df.drop(['time_in_hospital', 'weight', 'max_glu_serum', 'A1Cresult', 'medical_specialty', 'payer_code'], axis=1)
y = df['time_in_hospital']

# split into train and test sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.33, random_state=1, stratify=y)

# prepare input data
X_train_enc, X_test_enc = prepare_inputs(X_train, X_test)

# prepare output data
y_train_enc, y_test_enc = prepare_targets(y_train, y_test)

# feature selection

Preprocess Dataset - Casting and Imputing¶

        student_numerical_col_list, PREDICTOR_FIELD, categorical_impute_value='nan', numerical_impute_value=0)
processed_df.shape
Out[50]:
(54271, 32)

We will cast and impute the dataset before splitting so that we do not have to repeat these steps across the splits in the next step. For imputing, there can be deeper analysis into which features to impute and how to impute but for the sake of time, we are taking a general strategy of imputing zero for only numerical features.

If data is missing totally at random (whether a value is missing does not depend on any of the feature values of that item), then imputation can be appropriate. In contrast, if the chance for data to go missing for some object depends on the value of the features of that object, then you have a bigger problem. In that case imputation can create bias – as can any other method.

Replacing continuous data with the mean/median/mode is a common approach, but this can add variance and bias, and generally works better when the data size is small. Imputing zero for all numerical features in our case as a general strategy skews the data more towards zero –

For categorical data, a common approach is to assign a unique category. However, this adds less variance, and having another feature in the model while encoding may result in poor model performance – needless to say that we already have this option in place here.

Another common approach is to simply delete the row. This results in a robust model, since it does not have a high weightage. On the other side, we risk a loss of information and data, and this method particularly works poorly if the percentage of missing values is high (say 30%), compared to the whole dataset.

Which method to use to handle missing data has to be inspected on the feature level, as the strategy differs depending on the amount of missing values, type of missing values, and context of the feature.

Lastly, there is another way to impute our missing values: we could predict the missing values using the features which do not have missing values. This method may result in better accuracy, unless a missing value is expected to have a very high variance. One can experiment with different algorithms and check which gives the best accuracy instead of sticking to a single algorithm. This method is an improvement as long as the bias from the same is smaller than the omitted variable bias, though bias can also arise when an incomplete conditioning set is used for a categorical variable.

Split Dataset into Train, Validation, and Test Partitions¶

In order to prepare the data for being trained and evaluated by a deep learning model, we will split the dataset into three partitions, with the validation partition used for optimizing the model hyperparameters during training. One of the key parts is that we need to be sure that the data does not accidently leak across partitions.

Requirements for train/val/test sets:

  • Approximately 60%/20%/20% train/validation/test split
  • Randomly sample different patients into each data partition
  • IMPORTANT Make sure that a patient's data is not in more than one partition, so that we can avoid possible data leakage.
  • Make sure that the total number of unique patients across the splits is equal to the total number of unique patients in the original dataset
  • Total number of rows in original dataset = sum of rows across all three dataset partitions

Create Categorical Features with Tensorflow Feature Column API¶

Using the vocab file list from above that was derived fromt the features you selected earlier, please create categorical features with the Tensorflow Feature Column API.

We will use embedding_column and indicator_column to create the categorical feature columns.

indicator_column creates a one-hot vector from the column values. However, when the number of categories is very large (high cardinality), the length of the sparse one-hot encoded vector can become computationally very expensive for the model. In these cases, it is better to use embedding_columns, which outputs a lower dimensional dense vector, thus, speeding up the model training at a lower computational expense.

def build_baseline_model(train_ds, val_ds,  feature_layer,  epochs=5, loss_metric='mse', patience=3):
    model = tf.keras.Sequential([
        feature_layer,
        tf.keras.layers.Dense(150, activation='relu'),
        tf.keras.layers.Dense(75, activation='relu'),
        tfp.layers.DenseVariational(1+1, posterior_mean_field, prior_trainable),
        tfp.layers.DistributionLambda(
            lambda t:tfp.distributions.Normal(loc=t[..., :1],
                                             scale=1e-3 + tf.math.softplus(0.01 * t[...,1:])
                                             )
        ),
    ])
    model.compile(optimizer='rmsprop', loss=loss_metric, metrics=[loss_metric])
    early_stop = tf.keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor=loss_metric, patience=patience)     
    history = model.fit(train_ds, validation_data=val_ds,
                        callbacks=[early_stop],
                        epochs=epochs)
    return model, history

def load_baseline_model(feature_layer, checkpoint_path, loss_metric='mse'):
    model = tf.keras.Sequential([
        feature_layer,
        tf.keras.layers.Dense(150, activation='relu'),
        tf.keras.layers.Dense(75, activation='relu'),
        tfp.layers.DenseVariational(1+1, posterior_mean_field, prior_trainable),
        tfp.layers.DistributionLambda(
            lambda t:tfp.distributions.Normal(loc=t[..., :1],
                                             scale=1e-3 + tf.math.softplus(0.01 * t[...,1:])
                                             )
        ),
    ])
    model.compile(optimizer='rmsprop', loss=loss_metric, metrics=[loss_metric])
    model.load_weights(checkpoint_path)
    return model
In [69]:
def build_compile(model_choice, feature_layer, loss_metric, lr_i=1e-2):
    model = model_choice(feature_layer)
    lr_schedule = tf.keras.optimizers.schedules.ExponentialDecay(
        initial_learning_rate=lr_i,
        decay_steps=10000,
        decay_rate=0.95,
        staircase=True
    )
    optimizer = tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=lr_schedule)
    model.compile(optimizer=optimizer, loss=loss_metric, metrics=[loss_metric])
    return model

def build_diabetes_model(model_choice, train_ds, val_ds,  feature_layer,  epochs=5, loss_metric='mse', lr_i=1e-2):
    model = build_compile(model_choice, feature_layer, loss_metric, lr_i)
    
    checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint(weight_path,
                             monitor=loss_metric,
                             verbose=1, 
                             save_best_only=True,
                             mode='min',
                             save_weights_only = True)
    
    early_stop = EarlyStopping(monitor=loss_metric,
                               patience=10)
    
    callbacks_list = [checkpoint,
                      early_stop]
    
    history = model.fit(train_ds,
                        validation_data=val_ds,
                        callbacks=callbacks_list,
                        epochs=epochs, verbose=1)
    
    return model, history 

def load_model(model_choice, feature_layer, checkpoint_path, loss_metric='mse', lr_i=1e-2):
    model = build_compile(model_choice, feature_layer, loss_metric, lr_i)
    model.load_weights(checkpoint_path)
    return model

def plot_history(history, model_name):
    f = plt.figure()
    f.set_figwidth(10)

    plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'], label='val loss')
    plt.plot(history.history['loss'], label='train loss')
    plt.legend();
    plt.savefig('{}-history-plot.png'.format(model_name))

Pick Model & Model Evaluation Metrics¶

In [79]:
def get_model_performance(student_categorical_col_list,
                          student_numerical_col_list,
                          d_test,
                          diabetes_test_ds,
                          diabetes_model,
                          model_name):
    
    # Now that we have trained a model with TF Probability layers,
    # we can extract the mean and standard deviation for each prediction.
    feature_list = student_categorical_col_list + student_numerical_col_list
    diabetes_x_tst = dict(d_test[feature_list])
    diabetes_yhat = diabetes_model(diabetes_x_tst)
    preds = diabetes_model.predict(diabetes_test_ds)
    m, s = get_mean_std_from_preds(diabetes_yhat)
    
    # prediction output
    prob_outputs = {
        "pred": preds.flatten(),
        "actual_value": d_test['time_in_hospital'].values,
        "pred_mean": m.numpy().flatten(),
        "pred_std": s.numpy().flatten()
    }
    prob_output_df = pd.DataFrame(prob_outputs)
    
    # Convert Regression Output to Classification Output for Patient Selection
    # Given the output predictions, convert it to a binary label for whether the patient meets the time criteria or does not
    # (HINT: use the mean prediction numpy array).
    # The expected output is a numpy array with a 1 or 0 based off if the prediction meets or doesnt meet the criteria.
    student_binary_prediction = get_student_binary_prediction(prob_output_df, 'pred_mean')
    
    # Add Binary Prediction to Test Dataframe
    # Using the student_binary_prediction output that is a numpy array with binary labels,
    # we can use this to add to a dataframe to better visualize and also to prepare the data for the Aequitas toolkit.
    # The Aequitas toolkit requires that the predictions be mapped to a binary label for the predictions
    # (called 'score' field) and the actual value (called 'label_value').
    pred_test_df = add_pred_to_test(d_test, student_binary_prediction, ['race', 'gender'])

    y_val = pred_test_df['label_value']
    y_pred = pred_test_df['score']
    
    # get metrics    
    f1, class_report, auc, precision, recall = get_metrics(y_val, y_pred)
    tn, fp, fn, tp = confusion_matrix(y_val, y_pred).ravel()
    
    plot_auc(y_val, y_pred, model_name)
    plot_pr(y_val, y_pred, model_name)
    
    print("AUC: \t\t", auc)
    print("F1: \t\t", f1)
    print("Precision: \t", precision)
    print("Recall: \t", recall)
    print(f"\nTN: {tn}, FP: {fp}, FN: {fn}, TP: {tp}")
    print(class_report)
    
    return auc, f1, precision, recall, tn, fp, fn, tp, class_report, pred_test_df

We built a regression model that predicts the expected days of hospitalization time and then converted this to a binary prediction of whether to include or exclude that patient from the clinical trial. The threshold was set to time in hospital being bigger or equal to 5 days.

Here is an explanation of our metrics:

  • TP (True Positives): The correctly predicted positive values.
  • TN (True Negatives): The correctly predicted negative values.
  • FP (False Positives): When actual class is no and predicted class is yes, i.e. when the actual time in hospital was not sufficient but we predicted it would be. So they should not be included but we included them.

  • FN (False Negatives): When actual class is yes and predicted class is no, i.e. when actual time in hospital was sufficient but we predicted it would not be. So they should be included but we did not include them.

  • Precision is the ratio of correctly predicted positive observations to the total predicted positive observations. Of all the patients labeled as to include, how many are actually included? Calculated as TP / (TP+FN).

  • Recall (sensitivity) is the ratio of correctly predicted positive observations to all the observations in actual positive class. Of all the included patients, how many did we include? Calculated as TP / (TP+FP).

Possible scenarios:

  • Low recall, low precision: Our model straight up sucks :)
  • High recall, low precision: Our model includes a lot of patients, both patients that should be included but also those that should not be included.
  • Low recall, high precision: Our model is very picky. All patients that it labels as to include, should really be included. But because it is picky, it misses many other patients that should be included.
  • High recall, high precision: Ideal scenario!

Precision-recall trade-off: When we change the threshold for determining if a class is positive or negative, this action will "tilt the scales". It will either cause precision to increase and recall to decrease or vice versa. This means, If we increase precision, it will reduce recall, if we increase recall, it will reduce precision. We can never increase both, so this is what the precision-recall trade-off is about.

In the ROC curve, we plot sensitivity against (1-)specificity for different rheshold values. Each point onn the ROC represents a separate confusion matrix. AUC is the probability of correct ranking of a random positive-negative pair. A good ROC curve pushes towards the top-left side.

F1 score is the weighted average of precision and recall. This score takes both FP and FN into account. Accuracy works best if FP and FN have similar cost, but since the cost is different for us in a medical setting, it is better to look at both precision and recall. The score ranges between 0 and 1, with 1 being the best.

We've done a bit of model fine-tuning, and of course we will likely be able to yield better performance if we experimented some more with hyperparameters and architecture, or even choose to use a different model altogether. However, my first suggestion would be to go back to feature engineering and take a deep dive there, as good features really make and break any model.

Race and Gender Bias Analysis for Patient Selection¶

fpr_fairness = aqp.plot_fairness_group(fdf, group_metric='fpr', title=True)
In [95]:
p = aqp.plot_group_metric_all(clean_xtab, metrics=['tpr', 'fpr', 'ppr', 'pprev', 'fnr'], ncols=5)

How do we interpret above?

  • False Negative: The model predicted the patient did not stay in hospital for at least 5 days (thus not selected for drug testing), while they were.
  • False Positive: The model predicted the patient stayed in hospital for at least 5 days (thus selected for drug testing), while they were not.

Example: For FNR, the model was quite fair evaluating patients across gender. However, when a patient should be selected for drug testing, our model incorrectly recommended not selecting these patients 44% of the cases where the patient was Asian and 40% when the patient was Hispanic. There is a small bias towards these race groups compared to Caucasian (32%) and African American (32%).

Generally, deriving from the plot above, the model does not seem to have any noticeable bias towards gender. For PPR on race groups, we observe a 76% probability for Caucasians to be selected, heavily penalizing the other racial groups (Hispanic 2%, Asian 1%, African American 17%, and Other/Unknown 5%).
